TITLE: Implementing HUD Rendering with Color Interpolation in Fabric
DESCRIPTION: This code demonstrates how to register a HUD layer using Fabric's HudLayerRegistrationCallback. It creates a colored square that smoothly transitions between colors based on real-world time. The example shows proper initialization and implementation of a HUD rendering layer with animation.
SOURCE: https://github.com/FabricMC/fabric-docs/blob/main/translated/de_de/develop/rendering/hud.md#2025-04-05_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: java
CODE:
```
public class HudRenderingEntrypoint implements ClientModInitializer {
    // We create a new identifier for our layer
    private static final Identifier LAYER_ID = new Identifier("docs", "example_layer");

    @Override
    public void onInitializeClient() {
        // Register our hud layer
        HudRenderCallback.EVENT.register((matrices, tickDelta) -> {
            // This event is deprecated, and extremely limited. Don't use it.
        });

        // Register our layer using HudLayerRegistrationCallback
        HudLayerRegistrationCallback.EVENT.register((layerRegistrar) -> {
            // Register our layer
            layerRegistrar.registerLayer(LAYER_ID, (IdentifiedLayer) (drawContext, renderTickCounter) -> {
                // Get the width and height of the window
                int width = MinecraftClient.getInstance().getWindow().getScaledWidth();
                int height = MinecraftClient.getInstance().getWindow().getScaledHeight();

                // Get the current time in milliseconds
                long time = Util.getMeasuringTimeMs();

                // Use the time to create a sin wave between 0 and 1
                float sinWave = (float) Math.sin(time / 1000.0) * 0.5f + 0.5f;

                // Lerp between two colors using the sin wave
                int color = MathHelper.lerp(
                        sinWave,
                        0xFF0000FF, // Blue
                        0xFFFF0000  // Red
                );

                // Render a square in the top right corner
                drawContext.fill(width - 50, 10, width - 10, 50, color);
            });
        });
    }
}
```

